            <fr:title text="Can we treat \mathsf {\mathbf {*}} as \mathsf {\mathbf {N}}?">Can we treat <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex>?</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>Suppose we have a strong Kleene valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex>.
That valuation itself need not be a Dunn-Belnap valuation, as noted above, since it might assign the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> to some atomic sentence.
But perhaps we can <html:em>use</html:em> it to <html:em>find</html:em> a particular Dunn-Belnap valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> that we can work with.</html:p>
            <html:p>Here's one way we might do it.
For every atomic sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, then we let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u(A) = v(A)]]></fr:tex>.
That is, if we're already using a value that's present in the Dunn-Belnap structure, we leave it alone and let the Dunn-Belnap valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> match our strong Kleene valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> for that atomic sentence.
On the other hand, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>, then we let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
            <html:p>Now we've set up a way where, given any strong Kleene valuation, we can determine a Dunn-Belnap valuation, and we know how they're related for <html:em>atomic</html:em> sentences, because of how we've set them up: they match on values <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, and they also kind of match on other values, except that wherever the strong Kleene valuation has <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> the Dunn-Belnap valuation has <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex>, and vice versa.</html:p>
            <html:p>What about compound sentences, though?
Unlike atomic sentences, we can't just declare that these work however we want; we have tables to deal with in the two structures.
So we need to look into these tables.
As an example, let me reproduce the negation tables here:</html:p>
