            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>As I pointed out before, here we have agreement between these tables on what they do with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>.
But what about <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex>?
Here, too, we have a certain kind of "agreement": each of these values gets taken by negation to <html:em>itself</html:em>.
So if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>, and if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex> then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>3</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>22</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/005A/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>005A</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/005A/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Reasoning by induction">Reasoning by induction</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Here it helps to be a bit more precise in a certain kind of ritualised way.
(With all our symbols flying around, this is probably the class where you're most likely to accidentally summon a demon anyhow; let's lean into it!)
The ritualised reasoning I want to introduce here is called reasoning <html:em>by induction</html:em>.</html:p>
                <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:authors>
                      <fr:author>
                        <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                      </fr:author>
                    </fr:authors>
                    <fr:date>
                      <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                      <fr:month>3</fr:month>
                      <fr:day>22</fr:day>
                    </fr:date>
                    <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/005B/</fr:uri>
                    <fr:display-uri>005B</fr:display-uri>
                    <fr:route>/lectures/005B/</fr:route>
                    <fr:taxon>Side note</fr:taxon>
                  </fr:frontmatter>
                  <fr:mainmatter>
                    <html:p>Actually, there are at least two different kinds of reasoning that get called <html:em>reasoning by induction</html:em>, and they are very much not the same!
One is the kind that plays a role in the so-called <fr:link href="https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/induction-problem/" type="external">"problem of induction"</fr:link>; that's <html:em>not</html:em> what I'm talking about here.
The other is one that's sometimes called "mathematical induction" or "structural induction", and that's what we are doing.</html:p>
                  </fr:mainmatter>
                </fr:tree>
                <html:p>The core of the idea is this: suppose we want to securely demonstrate that <html:em>all formulas</html:em> are such-and-such a way.
The idea of induction doesn't depend on <html:em>what</html:em> we're trying to show about all formulas, so for now let's just say we want to show that all formulas are happy.</html:p>
                <html:p>We can use what we know about <fr:link href="/lectures/000G/" title="Languages" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/000G/" display-uri="000G" type="local">how formulas are built up</fr:link> to systematically think about all formulas, and make sure we haven't left any of them out.
Since there are <fr:link href="/lectures/000K/" title="Infinity; or, more than about six" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/000K/" display-uri="000K" type="local">more than six or seven</fr:link> formulas, we need some kind of system!
The structure of formulas themselves is a very useful system much of the time, and it's what I'll use here.</html:p>
                <html:p>We want to start, then, with the atomic sentences, showing that they are all happy.
In practice, how we do this will depend on what it is we're really showing about all sentences; induction provides us no help here.
But suppose we can do it: we've shown that all atomic sentences are happy.
</html:p>
                <html:p>What remains is all the compound sentences, and this is where induction really gives us its power.
All we need to do here is to show that <html:em>if</html:em> all the components of a compound sentence are happy, <html:em>then</html:em> the compound sentence itself is also happy.
That is, in showing that the compound sentence is happy, we can <html:em>help ourselves</html:em> to the assumption that all its components are happy.
</html:p>
                <html:p>This is important enough that it's handy to have a word for it:</html:p>
                <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:authors>
                      <fr:author>
                        <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                      </fr:author>
                    </fr:authors>
                    <fr:date>
                      <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                      <fr:month>3</fr:month>
                      <fr:day>23</fr:day>
                    </fr:date>
                    <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/005J/</fr:uri>
                    <fr:display-uri>005J</fr:display-uri>
                    <fr:route>/lectures/005J/</fr:route>
                    <fr:title text="Preservation">Preservation</fr:title>
                    <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
                  </fr:frontmatter>
                  <fr:mainmatter>
                    <html:p>A connective in a language <html:strong>preserves</html:strong> a property of sentences iff: whenever that connective is the main connective of a sentence, if all the components of that sentence have the property, then so does the sentence itself.</html:p>
                  </fr:mainmatter>
                </fr:tree>
                <html:p>So what we're aiming to do is to show that all the connectives <html:em>preserve</html:em> the property of happiness.</html:p>
                <html:p>Think about why this works: suppose it's true that all atomic sentences are happy, and that all the connectives preserve happiness.
How, then, could there ever be a sentence that wasn't happy?
How could it be built?
We have to start from atomic sentences that are happy, and build up using connectives that can't ever bring us from happy sentences to not-happy ones.
So any sentence we can manage to build in this way must be happy---but that's all the sentences!</html:p>
                <html:p>If we can show the two parts of what we need, then:
<html:ul><html:li>that all atomic sentences are happy, and</html:li>
<html:li>that all connectives preserve happiness,</html:li></html:ul>
then we've shown "by induction" that all sentences are happy.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>Okay, back to what we're doing.
Here, what we want to show about all formulas is a bit complex.
But really, it's exactly what we've set up to be true for all atomic sentences---we want to show that that's true of all sentences.
That is, we're going to reason by induction, but instead of showing that all formulas are "happy", we're going to show that all formulas <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> are such that:
<html:ul><html:li>if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u(A) = v(A)]]></fr:tex>, and</html:li>
<html:li>if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex>.</html:li></html:ul></html:p>
            <html:p>To show by induction that all formulas have this complex property, we start by showing that all atomic sentences have it.
Here our job is easy: the way we set up the Dunn-Belnap valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex>, it does exactly this for all atomic sentences!
So the first half of what we need is already done.</html:p>
            <html:p>The second half is to work connective by connective, and see that each connective preserves this property.
Consider negation, for example.
We want to see that, whenever any sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> has this property, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  A]]></fr:tex> also has the property.
So imagine that we have some sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> with the property.
Then one of three things is the case: either
<html:ul><html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = u(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, or</html:li>
<html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = u(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, or</html:li>
<html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex>.</html:li></html:ul></html:p>
            <html:p>Now, looking at our negation tables, we can see that these three cases give us, respectively:
<html:ul><html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  A) = u(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, or</html:li>
<html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  A) = u(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, or</html:li>
<html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex>.</html:li></html:ul>
And in all three of those cases, we can see that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  A]]></fr:tex> has the property we're concerned with.
So <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg ]]></fr:tex> preserves this property.
</html:p>
            <html:p>To finish the job, we need to think about every connective in turn.
I won't go through them all here, since it gets pretty repetitive.
But I will look at one binary and one nullary connective, so that you can see how this reasoning goes at various different arities.
You should read this looking for the <html:em>general pattern</html:em> of reasoning.
The details are important, but they are also just details.
Make sure you see the big picture too!
That way you can use this technique to answer your own questions (and puzzles).</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>3</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>23</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/005K/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>005K</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/005K/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="\lor  preserves the property"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lor ]]></fr:tex> preserves the property</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Let's look at a binary connective: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lor ]]></fr:tex>.
We want to show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lor ]]></fr:tex> preserves the property.
So consider any sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \lor  B]]></fr:tex>, and suppose that both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> have the property; we want to show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \lor  B]]></fr:tex> has it as well.</html:p>
                <html:p>This gives us <html:em>nine</html:em> possibilities to think through, as each of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> gives three possibilities: either it has value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> in both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex>, or it has <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex> in both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex>, or it has <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex>.
Since these are independent, and we have two components to consider, there are nine overall possibilities. 
These possibilities are nicely summed up in the strong Kleene table for disjunction, which also tells us <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A \lor  B)]]></fr:tex> for each of these possibilities:</html:p>
                <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:authors>
                      <fr:author>
                        <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                      </fr:author>
                    </fr:authors>
                    <fr:date>
                      <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                      <fr:month>3</fr:month>
                      <fr:day>23</fr:day>
                    </fr:date>
                    <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/005L/</fr:uri>
                    <fr:display-uri>005L</fr:display-uri>
                    <fr:route>/lectures/005L/</fr:route>
                  </fr:frontmatter>
                  <fr:mainmatter>
                    <html:table style="border-collapse: collapse;">
  <html:thead><html:tr>
    <html:td class="topedge leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lor ]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  </html:tr></html:thead>
  <html:tbody>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
  </html:tbody>
</html:table>
                  </fr:mainmatter>
                </fr:tree>
                <html:p>It remains, then, to check <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u(A \lor  B)]]></fr:tex> on these same nine possibilities.
Here we can start from the Dunn-Belnap table for disjunction, since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> is a Dunn-Belnap valuation:</html:p>
                <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:authors>
                      <fr:author>
                        <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                      </fr:author>
                    </fr:authors>
                    <fr:date>
                      <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                      <fr:month>3</fr:month>
                      <fr:day>14</fr:day>
                    </fr:date>
                    <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/0045/</fr:uri>
                    <fr:display-uri>0045</fr:display-uri>
                    <fr:route>/lectures/0045/</fr:route>
                  </fr:frontmatter>
                  <fr:mainmatter>
                    <html:table style="border-collapse: collapse;">
  <html:thead><html:tr>
    <html:td class="topedge leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lor ]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  </html:tr></html:thead>
  <html:tbody>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
  </html:tbody>
</html:table>
                  </fr:mainmatter>
                </fr:tree>
                <html:p>Notice, though, that we can ignore the row and the column headed by "<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex>".
After all, we're supposing that both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> have the property, and that means that both  <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u(A)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u(B)]]></fr:tex> must not be <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
                <html:p>Look at it, then, more like this:</html:p>
                <html:table style="border-collapse: collapse;">
  <html:thead><html:tr>
    <html:td class="topedge leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lor ]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge fade"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  </html:tr></html:thead>
  <html:tbody>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td class="fade"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge fade"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td class="fade"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td class="fade"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td class="fade"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td class="fade"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td class="fade"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td class="fade"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
  </html:tbody>
</html:table>
                <html:p>And now note, if you focus just on what's not faded out, how similar this looks to the strong Kleene table.
You can use these tables to walk through all nine possibilities, and see that in each case, indeed <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \lor  B]]></fr:tex> has the property.</html:p>
                <html:p>That is, suppose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = v(B) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>; then we are in the top left corner of the strong Kleene table.
Since both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> have the property, this means that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u(A) = u(B) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, so we are also in the top left corner of the Dunn-Belnap table.
Comparing those two top-left corners, we see that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A \lor  B) = u(A \lor  B) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>; so in this case <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \lor  B]]></fr:tex> has the property.</html:p>
                <html:p>That preceding paragraph is one of the nine cases that need considering.
Take a moment to walk through at least a few of the other cases at that level of detail, making sure you see how every sinew of the reasoning connects.
If you do it properly, you'll see that it really does work!</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>3</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>23</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/005M/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>005M</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/005M/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="\top  preserves the property"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\top ]]></fr:tex> preserves the property</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>As is usual, the situation with our nullary connectives is maybe a little weirder-feeling, but in fact much simpler.
Let's look at the case of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\top ]]></fr:tex>.
In both strong Kleene and Dunn-Belnap valuations, this sentence always receives the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>; so it has the property.
That's it!</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>3</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>28</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/005N/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>005N</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/005N/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Bringing it together">Bringing it together</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Let's take stock.
We've seen that, for any strong Kleene valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex>, we can set up a Dunn-Belnap valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> so that every atomic sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> has the following property:
<html:ul><html:li>if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u(A) = v(A)]]></fr:tex>, and</html:li>
<html:li>if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex>.</html:li></html:ul></html:p>
                <html:p>We've also seen that every connective preserves this property.
So we can conclude by induction that the property holds of <html:em>every</html:em> sentence, not just the atomic ones.</html:p>
                <html:p>This doesn't show that strong Kleene valuations <html:em>are</html:em> Dunn-Belnap valuations.
But it does show a way to translate any strong Kleene valuation into an importantly-related Dunn-Belnap valuation: leave all the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex> values alone, and change every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex>.
For now, put a pin in that; we'll come back to it in a moment.
We've got other possibilities to consider first!</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
